Air cargo plays a critical role in international trade, moving around seven trillion dollars’ worth of goods each year. Although it represents a smaller share of global trade by volume, it accounts for a large proportion of trade by value. As global trade continues to grow, so does the demand for fast and reliable air transport. 

The air cargo industry manages this demand by using speed and network access as its main strengths. Compared with other transport modes, air freight is significantly faster and often involves lower risk for high-value or time-critical goods. To meet this demand efficiently, most air cargo is carried in the belly holds of scheduled passenger aircraft, allowing airlines to use existing flights to transport goods alongside passengers. 

Airlines manage trade demand through scheduled services and planned capacity. Regular flight schedules give exporters and importers predictable departure and arrival times, supporting supply chains that rely on speed and reliability. When flights operate as planned and cargo is loaded as booked, international trade flows can be maintained consistently. 

However, demand for air cargo space constantly changes. Airlines regularly review available cargo capacity, especially on routes where demand is high or where air freight competes closely with sea freight. During peak demand periods, limited space can affect availability and pricing, requiring careful allocation of capacity. 

When direct flights are not available, demand is managed through indirect services. These routes include one or more transshipment points and allow cargo to move through airline networks even when there is no direct connection. While indirect routing increases flexibility, missed connections due to weather, passenger loads, or space constraints can affect delivery schedules. 

Freight forwarders also play a key role in managing demand by consolidating shipments. By combining cargo from multiple shippers into unit load containers, forwarders make efficient use of limited aircraft space. Consolidation allows smaller shipments to move as part of a larger load and enables airlines to schedule departures based on when sufficient cargo demand is available. 

Overall, the air cargo industry manages the demand of international trade through a combination of scheduled capacity, flexible routing, and consolidation strategies. These mechanisms allow global trade to continue moving quickly, even when demand fluctuates and space is limited.

